st common use case, which is the experienced user — explains why man pages tend to be cryptic for those unfamiliar with a particular command 11:08 lt; dancohengt; jgsmith: right. good point. 11:10 lt; bess_gt; in the omeka hacking talk we’re making unreasonable demands of the omeka dev team 11:10 lt; davelester___gt; 11:11 lt; dchudgt; jgsmith: does unix optimize for the most common use case, or the simplest, decomposed, filterable use case? 11:11 lt; asolovegt; it optimizes for the case of people who have write access to the man page in a project 11:11 lt; bess_gt; asolove++ # so true! 11:12 lt; jgsmithgt; well, most people using unix are experienced in unix — the inexperience period is short compared to the rest of a person’s career 11:12 lt; matthewgaventagt; nice parallel: in bibliography, we’re bordering on making unreasonable demands on the zotero team 11:12 lt; bess_gt; matthewgaventa: I’m going to make my unreasonable demands during the lunchtime zotero session 11:13 lt; jgsmithgt; doesn’t mean an interface should be poorly designed — but designed for the person familiar with the process or the concepts involved 11:13 lt; asolovegt; the design might encourage users to learn the underlying system 11:14 lt; jgsmithgt; asolove: -nod- — easier to do in a GUI than a CLI 11:15 lt; dancohengt; note to people making unreasonable demands of CHNMers: don’t make us release the hounds on you. 11:18 lt; epistemographergt; unreasonable demands++ 11:19 lt; dancohengt; fluidproject.org/ and Yahoo UI provide open source nice-looking widgets for websites 11:19 lt; dancohengt; that are tested across many browsers 11:20 lt; epistemographergt; for reference: URL I demo-ed is labs.nypl.org/projects/maps/transparent.html 11:40 lt; bess_gt; OAI/PMH plugin for omeka is fantastic. I’ve never cared deeply about OAI before, but I think I just started. 11:42 lt; elligt; bibliographicontology.com/ 11:50 lt; erazlogogt; use for upcoming mapping plugin in zotero–map your research trips by 