3882	Yes	The Loon has thought for some time that an inevitable battle in the struggle against paywalled research knowledge would occur when academe revolted in collective outrage against paywallers imposing severe punishment for an everyday academic practice. If publishers had won the Georgia State case, if they win on appeal and destroy e-reserves, if the Authors Guild had beaten Hathi Trust in court, if NPG hadn’t backed down in some fashion from its California price hike, those might have done it. Do Swartz’s suicide and the subsequent eruption of #pdftribute mean this is the proverbial it ? Not quite… but it’s closer than anything has yet been, and if the Loon worked for paywallers, she’d worry. Two truths dampen the backlash: first, Swartz was not himself an academic, so most academics do not feel directly attacked; and second, few academics can imagine breaking into a server closet with a laptop. Moreover, the mourning and anger for Swartz, heartfelt and activist though it is, appears not to have made the leap offline, and most of academe is still stubbornly, resolutely offline. Well, and one other thing: even online academe still doesn’t understand open access . Just look at the several open-access–related misstatements in that article, written by a young (so ignorance cannot be fobbed off on age) anthropologist (nor humanism). What #pdftribute does bring to the table is a new urgency for those taking part in it, an urgency that changes “open access? … meh” to “there is good and cogent reason to make our work open.” That belief is new to most #pdftributers, as it was to many Cost of Knowledge signatories , and while the initial impulse will unquestionably fade, the belief likely won’t. In other words, paywallers are having their apathetic silent majority chipped away at, again. That’s not good for them. The Loon grudges the price. Exceedingly grudges it. Swartz was her kind of people, never mind that no one should die the way he did. She does believe that Swartz would approve #pdftribute and court longer-range impact for it, however, and she will do what is in her to bring that about. 
3883	Yes	“So,” a friend of the Loon’s asked her a short while ago, “how does it feel to be unemployable?” No, no, now, stop, this truly was a friend, and the query was not meant to hurt. It’s a legitimate question: when one has joined the exodus or been shown the door for any of a number of reasons, what next? Well, if one is like the Loon, grief, anger, and recrimination ensue. They take some time to climb out of—the Loon is still working on it, though she’s nearer the top than the bottom of the chasm, finally—but unless permitted to run riot, these natural and ordinary states of mind don’t generally inhibit important parts of moving on, such as sorting out how to put fish on the table. The Loon should perhaps be more specific about what she means when she says she is unemployable. She is far too far along in her career, and too well-established in certain among her specialties, for librarianship to permit her to “start over,” even in a different specialty or another type of library. Lateral moves are near-impossible because of the Loon’s abrasive, vocal iconoclasm; she is disliked or feared or both at many employers she might otherwise move to, and her reputation “in the cloud” is not good. (Never underestimate how much hearsay and gossip fuels the average search committee.) Even were that not so, the Loon is decidedly wary of the jobs she left, and doesn’t really care to take another stab at them. Neither scholarly communication nor research-data management gets a fair shake in most libraries; why knowingly endure (much less court) being set up to fail yet again? Her career boasts sufficient longevity to try for the lower echelons of library management, were it not that her specialties were organizationally distinguished by their lone-wolfness, such that she has very little experience to suggest to a search committee by way of management qualifications. (Not nothing exactly, nor does she think herself wholly unsuited for the role; but what experience she does have does not paint her as the Organization Loon most libraries seek in their line supervisors and middle managers.) With down, sideways, and up equally out of reach, the remaining option is “out.” The Loon perforce chose that option. The difficulty she finds in discussing it is that “out” leads to a labyrinth of forking paths, difficult to generalize from. The Loon tested several possible “out”s, rejecting some and being rejected by others, before settling where she is, and she may well not be done with change—that depends on how the results of her latest negotiated workplace alteration play out, and she won’t know that for a year or more yet. Chaotic and uncertain though it’s been, the Loon is generally happy with how the uncertain period has turned out. She kept fish on the table (in fact, she scored herself a decent raise), which means that she now knows from the tip of her bill to the last feather in her tail that she can keep fish on the table, in spite of everything. This is useful and comforting knowledge. It is, in a way, safer to know oneself able to earn one’s fish from bits and bobs than to feel bound to acquiesce to a stunningly bad job merely because it is stable. That said, the Loon is a bird of habit and routine, wandering migration not her preferred life. She has therefore found a new pond to settle in, the library school where she teaches. The Loon is thoroughly delighted with the autonomy, creature comforts, mutual trust, mutual aid and protection, and quality of leadership provided by her new pond. Moreover, the identical qualities that landed the Loon in vast amounts of trouble in librarianship turn out to be valuable assets to an instructor. Outspokenness, opinionated irreverence, hamminess—these are no more than what it takes to face classrooms week in and week out. The Loon’s students can handle abrasive iconoclasm aimed at librarianship; it doesn’t hit them where they live yet, and they’re still open-minded enough to find iconoclasm profitably eye-opening. Perhaps most important, the Loon’s teaching work feels immediately, obviously useful and productive in a way her library work sadly almost never did. That is not to say the Loon enjoys perfect contentment, though the reasons she doesn’t are thoroughly idiosyncratic and likely none too wise. Her current employment does not offer quite the same sense of directly making history, of idealistically refashioning the world, as her old; missing that larger sense of purpose sometimes makes the Loon fretful. Her work is also removed from certain kinds of praxis and praxis-based learning that she was fond of—not unlike the shift from computer programmer to project manager that many programmers deplore—though she has plans in the works that may fill that hole somewhat. The Loon also doesn’t enjoy knowing that she can’t go back to librarianship even if she wants to. She didn’t go to library school to become a library-school instructor! She loves her own peculiar brand of librarianship, as cruel to her as it was, and she never thought she’d be shut away from it for good and all. That hurts. On bad days it’s a severe self-confidence sapper. As the Loon rebuilds her professional life, though, the hurt lessens as the attractions of the new situation grow, and as she learns different, often better means of exerting her will and talents to work toward desired change in the world. As for her shattered professional reputation, the Loon has given up on mending the pieces, and certainly on lamenting them, believing (with, of late, some supporting evidence) that she’ll do better building anew. The Loon is a great believer in serendipity, too. As she remakes herself, and turns that remade self loose to fly and swim and waddle about, opportunities will likely turn up. Who knows? Perhaps she isn’t lost to librarianship forever. Stranger things have happened, including to loons. How does unemployability feel, then? Sometimes raw and painful. Sometimes wistful, blurred with regrets. Mostly, though, it feels vigorous and constructive and worthwhile. That’s more than the Loon expected, and quite possibly more than she deserves, and she’s nothing if not grateful for that. 
3884	Yes	The Loon saw John Wilbanks express some uncharacteristic frustration earlier today on Twitter. She understands it. Oh, does she! A goodly part of the reason the Loon is unemployable is that she was repeatedly hired to run her head into the wall between the world and open access until the wall broke. The wall didn’t break; the Loon did. Some small still-reptilian segment of the Loon’s avian brain absolutely rages when she sees parvenus grabbing spotlights, swallowing up the open-access discourse, sailing gaily into clear waters the Loon spent long dark painful years trying to clear the weeds and algae from. How dare they . They didn’t work and fight and swallow endless gallons of insult and scorn and break their much-desired careers over open access, oh no. How dare they swan about on it now ? Most of them are likely fair-weather friends at best; they’ll swan onto the next thing shortly, leaving those of us who genuinely believe behind to pick up the real work again—the work they won’t have done any of, of course. (It’s worse when the parvenus show their undergarments in public. So many of them don’t understand what they’re prating on about!) Even when the parvenus lionize their elders-in-struggle, it can hurt. The Loon has been called “inspiring,” “groundbreaking,” her work an “instant classic.” Starry-eyed youngsters (even not-so-youngsters) have told her they want to be like her, not in the least understanding the prices the Loon has paid to be who she is—worse, not offering to support her in her continuing struggles. None of this adulation makes the Loon happy any more. It irritates her, frankly. The price was too damned high, the tangible personal rewards damned near nonexistent. Yes, the Loon understands. Here’s the thing, though. The thing is, this sort of interaction is what happens when we’re finally winning: winning mindshare , winning progress, winning allies. If we care to continue to win, we don’t alienate the parvenus ; we welcome them and do what we can to turn them into substantive contributors to—yes, even owners of—the movement. Eyes on the prize. This is what happens when we’re winning. To keep winning, we must suppress our annoyance—our justified, legitimate annoyance—and smile. This is unquestionably both unfair and difficult, but it remains much the best of the available options. Parvenus: forgive your elders our occasional lashing-out, please. It’s not that we grudge your presence; we don’t, no matter how much we growl. It’s that we have fought and been hurt. Acknowledge that, when you can, and try to remember to help us as you lend your new-broom enthusiasm to the movement. 
3885	Yes	Oh, yes. When the Loon asked for ignorant statements about open access to be challenged in 2013, this is exactly what she meant . She is particularly enamored of this bon mot : “Just because some people want stuff for free doesn’t mean that all people who want to free stuff are bad.” Also, this segment: A lot of the time when people like Rob Weir say this they believe that they are the hard-nosed realists who are speaking truth to a bunch of naive activists. In fact, the opposite is true — it is inevitably those people who have thought least about scholarly publishing and know little about open access who make this claim. Yes, indeed. Now, the Loon confesses she isn’t over-fond of the blatant ageism later in the post. Nonetheless, she enjoyed the post and agrees that the editorial it is challenging was wretchedly, shamefully ignorant. 
3886	Yes	Though Library Day in the Life has closed as a semi-organized event, the Loon isn’t quite ready to bid it farewell forever. Therefore we shall today have The Loon, Her Work Day, 24 January 2013. 5:15 am: The Loon awakens because a cat has sulkily decided it’s too cold in the nest, ergo crawling under the covers is appropriate. Accommodate cat; return to something vaguely like sleep. 6:20 am: Awaken again; arise. The cat’s irritation is the cat’s problem. Pull on additional plumage against the (yes, quite) cold nest. Go to the nest’s top story to turn on laptop and anti-seasonal-depression light. (The Loon lives in the Frozen North. The light helps.) 6:20-7:20 am: Check the Loon’s favorite webcomics (no xkcd today). Skim the Chronicle of Higher Education and Inside Higher Ed. Skim professional newsreader (yes, the Loon has a personal one as well, with a separate list of feeds); nothing needing bookmarking or saving for a closer read today. Catch up on a couple of casual browser games in the meanwhile. 7:20 am: Turn off light and laptop; go back downstairs to shift plumage and collect impedimenta for work. 7:40 am: Swim out of the nest toward work. 8:00 am: Arrive in office; divest extra plumage and impedimenta. Fetch physical mail; greet folk in main office. 8:05 am: Video upload left to run overnight did not complete. Growl. Restart it, in smaller chunks this time. Check signups for an event the Loon is responsible for. Volley some email and other social-media conversations. Start music playing (on the Loon’s iPod, so as not to serenade the entire floor of the building). 8:20 am: Check the class boards for discussion. Answer what needs answering. Deal with the usual raft of early-semester course-management-system glitches. Mull previous post over in rear of small avian brain. 9:00 am: Dash off previous post , pausing twice to direct people who are lost in the Loon’s building (it happens, especially at this time of the semester). 9:20 am: Read mailing lists and recheck feeds while taking care of various administrative and teaching chores. 10:15 am: Settle in to serious work on a continuing-education course. Finish a week’s “lecture” (actually written, not spoken; the topic at hand rewards precision), start on a quizlet. 10:45 am: Get involved in a Twitter conversation regarding previous post . 10:55 am: Wrench attention back to course. Finish quizlet. Revise “lecture.” Revise it again. Revise it more . 12:30 pm: Notice distinct lack of lunch. Rectify same, eating at desk because the Loon is both a busy and a messy creature. Start in on next lesson. 3:05 pm: Another half-week’s lesson, including accompanying quizlet, done. (This one was image-heavy, and the Loon takes a long time to make images.) Debate whether to start on the next chunk, despite brain-fog. Decide to take a break, dealing with an advising question in email and checking the (oh, dear, rather full) feedreader instead of charging into the next lesson. 3:20 pm: Happen across this blog post during feedreader peregrinations. Decide to blog it. Blog it. 3:35 pm: Finish email and feedreader. Decide to take a stab at starting the next half-lesson. Sketch out its outline in headings and subheadings. Write text, admitting ruefully that much of it may need rewriting tomorrow with a clearer head. 3:45 pm: Realize the video uploads have been forgotten. Sigh, check them. They worked this time! Start more video uploading. Back to lesson-writing. 3:59 pm: Realize there is a major thinko in the previous half-lesson that carries into the syllabus. Sigh heavily . Decide to deal with it later. Make a note in to-do list about it. 4:06 pm: Check email one last time for fires to put out. Finding none, post blog post, shut down computer and iPod in orderly fashion, and resume outdoor plumage for the swim home. The Loon hopes you enjoyed your day as much as she (despite growls and sighs) did hers. 
