4215	Yes	 The PressForward Project amp; Scholarly Communication on the Open Web , a project briefing presented at CNI’s fall 2012 membership meeting by Dan Cohen and Joan Fragaszy Troyano from the Roy Rosenzweig Center for History amp; New Media at George Mason University, is now available on CNI’s two video channels: YouTube : Vimeo : http://vimeo.com/58456934 A healthy ecosystem for scholarly communication requires a continuum from independently distributed work to post-publication peer review. With funding from the Sloan Foundation, the Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media at George Mason University created the PressForward project to explore and produce the best means for collecting, screening, and drawing attention to the vast expanse of scholarship that is currently decentralized across the web or does not fit into traditional genres such as the journal article or the monograph. This video provides an overview of current efforts to distribute and evaluate scholarly work available on the open web, and an explanation of the experimental methods behind PressForward’s Digital Humanities Now and Journal of Digital Humanities . It also includes a preview of the open source adaptations to WordPress software that PressForward is developing to enable scholarly communities to easily aggregate, select, and credit work published on the open web. Previously-released video from CNI’s fall 2012 meeting: - What Is College For? The Future of Higher Education (Hunter R. Rawlings III, Association of American Universities) http://youtu.be/zDLuCjCglDg - MOOCs, Mobility, and Changing Scholarly Practice: CNI’s Perspective on 2012 and 2013 (Cliff Lynch, CNI) http://youtu.be/Fvys5VZrjsI - Massive Open Online Courses as Drivers for Change (Lynne O’Brien, Duke U.) http://youtu.be/UbK0i4mhpWU Look for more announcements soon on videos of other sessions from the fall 2012 CNI meeting. To see all videos available from CNI, visit CNI’s video channels on YouTube ( http://www.youtube.com/cnivideo ) and Vimeo ( http://vimeo.com/channels/cni ). 
4216	Yes	 Figure 1: Otter Trail, South Africa Early paleoanthropologists worked in isolated groups with an archaeological or medical background. Fossil sites were usually located accidentally by mining companies or geologists. Since these early stages, the field of paleoanthropology has expanded to include many disciplines including biology, botany, ecology, functional morphology, and even genetics. Members of each of these fields now work together, employing interdisciplinary methods to reconstruct the past. Anemone et al. (2011) breaks the history of African fieldwork in paleoanthropology into three stages: the single-investigator, the interdisciplinary approach, and the return to the laboratory. Each stage led to the next, starting from the single-investigator, such as Broom, Dart, and the early work of the Leakey’s. The Leakey’s paved the way for the second stage: the interdisciplinary approach. F. Clark Howell, took the Leakey’s approach one step further by bringing together scientists from a variety of disciplines including geology, botany, and paleontology. Anemone et al. define the last stage as a progression beyond collaboration and a return to the laboratory with the advances in technology. Instead of plaster casts, technology allows for 3-D reconstructions, imaging, and scanning. In the field, fossil sites are no longer identified through accidental discovery or haphazard searching. Instead, remote sensing and geographic information systems (GIS) are being used to identify potential sites. Figure 2: Dr. Snow’s original cholera map which identified the Broad Street pump as the source of the epidemic. From the beginnings of GIS with mapping of a cholera epidemic, to more recently the hunt for Osama bin Laden, this science has a myriad of applications. As GIS increases in popularity, the science behind the software evolves as well. Applications of GIS include analyzing, measuring, storing and characterizing spatial data. A GIS can go beyond the raw data by manipulating the data points to interpolate between points, resample to decrease redundancy, and project or transform between raster and vector data sets. Additionally, new layers can be calculated through surface analysis. Water flow, slope, aspect, and viewsheds are all layers that can be calculated from the raw data. Moreover, raster and vector layers can be combined with a triangular irregular network (TIN) to create 3-dimensional images of surfaces. Shadowing can be added via the hillshade tool to highlight different features of the surface. Utilizing map algebra, areas that have a specific list of features can be identified. Anemone et al. describe methods in which GIS can be utilized to identify areas where fossilized remains are likely. Geological maps and lithological maps provide valuable information on the features and types of rocks present in specific areas. Further, by combining these data with remote sensing data, patterns can be identified. By ground-truthing areas with likely fossil sites, these patterns can be developed into predictive models to locate new fossil sites.  Anemone et al. applied principal components analysis to their remote sensing data and derived false color images from the eigenvectors, but they did not discuss what the results would indicate. Anemone et al. applied these techniques to their areas of research in the Great Divide Basin of Wyoming. They utilized Landsat 7 ETM+ data with unsupervised classification to identify statistical clusters of land cover. Then a bedrock geology map and known fossil sites were added. Next, they interpolated the topography of the surface at the Eocene-Oligocene boundary by interpolating between 69 points where the boundary is preserved and exposed. Similarly, the surface topography of the Late Cretaceous period was evaluated. Using the differences between these three topographic maps, Anemone et al. were able to evaluate the total amount of uplift between the erosional topography of the Eocene to present day. The elevation estimates derived from the GIS model were consistent with other estimates and to ground-truthing in the area. Surprisingly, these techniques have already been applied to the search for fossil hominins with success. Starting in 1988, Bernard Asfaw and Tim White, along with some NASA scientists utilized these techniques to investigate the previously unexplored areas of the Ethiopian Rift and Afar Depression. The Fejej site, excavated by John Fleagle and his crew, was one result of this analysis. Fleagle found vertebrates from the middle Miocene, Pliocene mammals, and Australopithecus afarensis dental remains dated to 3.7 million years ago. Kesem-Kebena was also located utilizing these techniques, and the previously unexplored site provided a wealth of well-preserved fossils and archaeological evidence including Acheulean bifaces. Despite the success of this project, few others have utilized this technology to identify fossil hominin sites. While paleoanthropology has been hesitant to adopt GIS techniques, paleontologists have utilized these resources to not only locate possible vertebrate sites, but also identify tracks such as the dinosaur tracksites at Red Gulch in Wyoming. The tracksites were mapped by integrating close-range and aerial photography, digital terrain models from satellite imagery, and subsurface geophysical imaging techniques. Hominin fossil sites such as the famous Laetoli and Langebaan Lagoon sites could also be mapped with these techniques. GIS techniques can also be applied at a micro level to the field of functional morphology began utilizing GIS to analyze the functionality of teeth by differentiating between species based on diet. Extant species are first classified by patterns of wear, and then the patterns are extrapolated to extinct species using GIS. Interestingly, dental topographic analysis has identified patterns between diet, wear, and dental topography. In this article Anemone et al. usefully identified several applications for GIS in the field of anthropology. They also recognized that the tools provided by a GIS are underutilized by the discipline. As remote sensing increases in popularity, the use of GIS will likely also increase as it is one of the most powerful methods to analyze spatial data. [Carrie A. Healy] —————– Anemone RL, Conroy GC, Emerson CW. 2011. GIS and paleoanthropology: Incorporating new approaches from the geospatial sciences in the analysis of primate and human evolution. Yearbook of Physical Anthropology 54:19-46. Figure 1: Courtesy of Wikipedia Commons; file is from public domain. http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Otter_Trail05.jpg Figure 2: Courtesy of Wikipedia Commons; file is from public domain. http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Snow-cholera-map.jpg 
4217	Yes	 As the managing editor at a big city newspaper, I learned about journalism psychology. I could call reporters in the middle of the night, tell them something was on fire and no matter how senior they were, they would drop everything and go. A little cursing, maybe, but no argument. News happens. That’s just the way it is. You deal with it. Picture that same veteran reporter coming in after the fire. If I told him I needed him to give up his desk and sit on the other side of the newsroom to write the story, there would be hell to pay. “This is MY spot,” he would growl. A lot of cursing, maybe. That’s journalism psychology. It is fine for news to change every single second. It is not fine to change the way we do the news. News changes, craft doesn’t. Deadlines can do this to people. Look at hospital emergency rooms or military combat units. Stick to the basics, or things turn ugly. In newspapers in particular, being a workplace fundamentalist worked. A notebook, a pencil, a manual typewriter. That’s all a reporter needed in 1870. That’s all we needed in 1970. Change came in the form of electric typewriters, mainframes, dummy terminals, personal computers, smart phones. We had to learn new ways to put the story onto the news assembly line. But that was nothing. Now, important new tools are coming monthly. This has made some of the older folks a little crazy. They rail against “fads” and “gizmos.” Most of us don’t have that luxury. So  American Press Institute ,  Poynter Institute  and  Knight Foundation  have launched a series of tutorial webinars to help media people learn to use new tools as fast as they’re coming out.  DocumentCloud  was the first:  the tutorial  showed how to set up an account and immediately start using the tool. Hundreds of attendees logged in. They learned how the tool tames simple documents from any journalistic beat. They learned advanced uses, like the USA Today quot; Ghost Factories quot; investigation showing toxic wastes at abandoned factories across America. The  next tutorial  is on the AP’s cool document mining tool,  Overview . I asked Knight’s  Michael Maness  and the  Journalism and Media Innovation team  what tools journalists should be learning. In time, the tool tutorials will get to all of them. Here’s Maness#39; list: DocumentCloud : Six hundred newsrooms use it to manage, annotate and publish documents. It lets reporters share information across newsrooms, which, if you have thousands of Sarah Palin emails to go through, is really useful. 
